Whenever we have incidents of re- form, the reform is distinctly volun- tary. Before his ministry he grew in favour with men, and during that

ministry with men who knew them- selves sinners‚ and we know that men are so constituted that he who habitu— ally finds fault does not grow in favour with them. It may be urged that there was about him a supernatural grace which disarmed the sinner of his natural dislike for reproof. Why, then, did not ' this supernatural grace operate with the separatists, whom he certainly did con— stantly reprove? It cannot have been by accident that the Gospel incident-s are selected. If there is no record of Jesus publicly finding fault with men of vicious habits, it is because he did not do it.
